Creating a solar system simulation using HTML, CSS, and JavaScript is a fascinating project that can help you understand and visualize the dynamics of our solar system. While the astrophysical data for each planet is readily available, the complexity of simulating the gravitational interactions accurately would typically require more advanced tools and languages. However, for a simplified simulation, we can use basic physics principles to model the motion of planets under the influence of gravity.

Here's a simplified approach to get you started:

1. **HTML for Structure**:
   You'll need a basic HTML structure to contain your simulation. You can use a `<div>` to act as the canvas for your solar system.

2. **CSS for Styling**:
   Use CSS to style your solar system. You can position the planets and stars using CSS transforms and animations.

3. **JavaScript for Logic**:
   JavaScript will handle the logic of the simulation, including calculating the positions of the planets over time based on their orbits.

### Step-by-Step Guide:

#### 1. HTML Setup:

```html
<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8">
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
    <title>Solar System Simulation</title>
    <link rel="stylesheet" href="style.css">
</head>
<body>
    <div id="solar-system"></div>
    <script src="script.js"></script>
</body>
</html>
```

#### 2. CSS Styling:

```css
#solar-system {
    width: 100vw;
    height: 100vh;
    perspective: 1000px;
    display: flex;
    justify-content: center;
    align-items: center;
}

.planet {
    width: 10px; /* Adjust size */
    height: 10px;
    background-color: #000; /* Change color */
    position: absolute;
    border-radius: 50%;
}

.sun {
    width: 50px; /* Adjust size */
    height: 50px;
    background-color: #FFF; /* Change color */
    position: absolute;
    border-radius: 50%;
}
```

#### 3. JavaScript Logic:

```javascript
// Constants
const G = 6.67430e-11; // Gravitational constant
const solarSystemRadius = 500; // Adjust based on your needs

// Planets data
const planets = [
    { name: 'Sun', mass: 1.989e30, position: { x: 0, y: 0, z: 0 }, velocity: { x: 0, y: 0, z: 0 } },
    // Add data for other planets...
];

// Simulation loop
function simulate() {
    requestAnimationFrame(simulate);

    // Calculate forces
    for (let i = 0; i < planets.length; i++) {
        const planet1 = planets[i];
        for (let j = i + 1; j < planets.length; j++) {
            const planet2 = planets[j];
            const dx = planet2.position.x - planet1.position.x;
            const dy = planet2.position.y - planet1.position.y;
            const dz = planet2.position.z - planet1.position.z;
            const distance = Math.sqrt(dx * dx + dy * dy + dz * dz);
            const force = G * planet1.mass * planet2.mass / (distance * distance);

            planet1.velocity.x += (dx / distance) * force / planet1.mass;
            planet1.velocity.y += (dy / distance) * force / planet1.mass;
            planet1.velocity.z += (dz / distance) * force / planet1.mass;

            planet2.velocity.x -= (dx / distance) * force / planet2.mass;
            planet2.velocity.y -= (dy / distance) * force / planet2.mass;
            planet2.velocity.z -= (dz / distance) * force / planet2.mass;
        }
    }

    // Update positions
    for (let i = 0; i < planets.length; i++) {
        const planet = planets[i];
        planet.position.x += planet.velocity.x;
        planet.position.y += planet.velocity.y;
        planet.position.z += planet.velocity.z;

        // Keep planets within the solar system radius
        if (planet.position.x > solarSystemRadius) {
            planet.position.x = -solarSystemRadius;
            planet.velocity.x = -planet.velocity.x;
        }
        if (planet.position.x < -solarSystemRadius) {
            planet.position.x = solarSystemRadius;
            planet.velocity.x = -planet.velocity.x;
        }
        if (planet.position.y > solarSystemRadius) {
            planet.position.y = -solarSystemRadius;
            planet.velocity.y = -planet.velocity.y;
        }
        if (planet.position.y < -solarSystemRadius) {
            planet.position.y = solarSystemRadius;
            planet.velocity.y = -planet.velocity.y;
        }
        if (planet.position.z > solarSystemRadius) {
            planet.position.z = -solarSystemRadius;
            planet.velocity.z = -planet.velocity.z;
        }
        if (planet.position.z < -solarSystemRadius) {
            planet.position.z = solarSystemRadius;
            planet.velocity.z = -planet.velocity.z;
        }
    }

    // Render planets
    const solarSystem = document.getElementById('solar-system');
    for (let i = 0; i < planets.length; i++) {
        const planet = planets[i];
        const planetElement = document.createElement('div');
        planetElement.classList.add('planet');
        planetElement.style.transform = `translate(${planet.position.x}px, ${planet.position.y}px)`;
        solarSystem.appendChild(planetElement);
    }
}

// Start the simulation
simulate();
```

This example provides a basic framework for a solar system simulation. It calculates the gravitational forces between planets and updates their positions accordingly. The simulation is quite simplified and doesn't account for many real-world complexities, such as the elliptical orbits of planets or the gravitational influences of other celestial bodies.

To enhance this simulation, you could:
- Add more realistic orbital mechanics.
- Implement elliptical orbits.
- Include other celestial bodies like asteroids, comets, or moons.
- Add user interaction, such as zooming in and out or changing the simulation speed.

This project is a great way to learn about physics, programming, and how to visualize complex systems. Enjoy your simulation!

